Text.Value: So you do believe he's working for the cult?
Maybe we should have killed him while we had the opening.
The cult has other ways of controlling people. Infection, indoctrination...
Come, then. We need a lead - and bullying this banker ought to make me feel better.
It is some defect of the mind, I think - to stubbornly insist you are following the light, even as you blunder through the darkness.
So he's some hero of prophecy?
I cannot call myself a particularly good friend. But I am his friend - and I cannot let Nine-Fingers have him.
Bastard.
Because who would question a statue to our friend, thinking Minsc of Rashemen had returned to a hero's welcome in Rashemen?
Assuming Minsc has not since tripped and fallen into a demi-plane, or some such.
No. He is an idiot who pissed off some gutter-mage with a flair for petrification. To this day, I still don't know all the details.
I made the right decision. But... I do not like how easily I made it. Minsc would have never left me behind, no matter what happened.
There must be something in the vaults the great Chosen are after. All the more reason to get there - swiftly.
I... am sure you meant that to be comforting.
You saw the fool - hanging on the doppelganger's every word, for no other reason than that it wears my face.
That was much Minsc's feeling, too. Perhaps I shouldn't be working so hard to bring you two together.
Just... help me save him. You might see why I didn't question a bit of peace and quiet.
Then that's what we'll do. But I wanted to discuss something else.
So dramatic. 'Abandoned' is a strong word, for one.
You focus on the goal while I slobber on about things I cannot change. Irritating.
Why? We know Minsc is alive - now we just have to find him.
I don't even know how he was freed. Harper work would take me from the city - sometimes for years at a time.
You abandoned him for a century. It's understandable you don't want to do it again.
Are you sure we shouldn't just let the Guild take care of this?
Maybe you haven't changed as much as you think.
No? It was a statue, dedicated to one of the city's lost heroes. Only it was that hero - Minsc, frozen in stone for a century. And freed, the story goes, in the city's hour of need.
The few occasions I visited his monument, well... I took it as a moment for reflection. To think of old friends, and the fight I had to continue in their name.
Are you sure you want to find him? It sounds like he's cursed.
I have no reason to doubt the guildmaster's information. Only her conclusions.
I am sorry, but... I am just tired.

EditorData.NodeContext: Anger tailing off into tiredness for real - her low point

Text.Value: I grow tired of these false faces. Every corner we turn, another - and now it is my face they use to turn Minsc against us.

EditorData.NodeContext: Quiet anger. Her low point - not quite giving in to desperation, but almost - coming out as frustration instead.

Text.Value: No, but snotting into my sleeve while there is still work to do is.
Of course you're tired - you're ancient. But we still have work to do.
How could he have been stuck that way for a century?
You don't have to explain, Jaheira. You're worried for your friend - it's not a crime.
Hahahahahahaha.
That is his problem entire. The past century left Minsc unchanged. And so he believes the world has never changed - that I have not.
For every strange situation he finds himself in, he wanders right back out of it again. Just a century later, sometimes.
Enough sulking, Harper. Now's not the time to grow soft.
Only what we heard from Keene. He seems to have sprung up while we were out in the shadow-lands.
For Minsc, it is downright subtle. He shrugged at the whole affair - I still don't know how he came to be petrified.
What is it?
Minsc must have a way in, but he's never had much use for coin beyond whatever sharp steel it could buy.
Don't worry. We'll save him - it might not even take a hundred years this time.
I do not think there will be much care involved, if we let Nine-Fingers get to him first.
But do you know how Minsc - a human - passed those years? I'll give you a hint: they named him the 'Beloved Ranger'.
Or perhaps the defect is mine.
*The name strikes a dim memory: a monument to a hero on one of the city's squares, which had turned out to be the hero himself, frozen in stone until the city's hour of need.*
Come, then. We need a lead on where these shapeshifters have fled to - let us see what hints they left behind in the vault.
*You recall the urban myth that trickled through the Lower City fest-halls some years back - a hero who had been turned into a statue, returning to life in the city's hour of need.*
Ah. 'Stone Lord'. That's a little on the nose.
And you stared right back without even realising it was him.
Probably we should have - and yet we both stayed our hands.
Turn to other topics.
I did. On occasion, I even found myself critiquing the stone-work. 'Surely his head was not so large as this?'
You have to admit - that's a little funny.
And during all my self-serious brooding that big, dumb, insufferable buffoon was staring me in the face.
...A terrible rallying speech. No poetry. Not even a little pat on the head.
The Time of Troubles ended almost a century and a half ago. I weathered the years between with all the elven grace you have no doubt come to expect.
The Stone Lord she describes sounds nothing like Minsc. As for the name, well... a bad joke, perhaps.
What do you know of the Stone Lord?
The Counting House. More bastion than bank, I'm afraid.
It doesn't matter. We have to find him.
When I left Minsc to this fate, I believed I had no choice. I believe it still - we were ignorant of our enemy, unarmed against the cult.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Pausing to take a deep breath - then telling us what's actually bothering her.
EditorData.NodeContext: Pausing to take a deep breath, telling us what's actually been gnawing at her all this time

Text.Value: I hope you find yourself amusing, at least. Come, then - to the Counting House.
Hah, you think I flatter myself in believing it is my face alone that Minsc follows? Malar mark me, but I find myself hoping he is tadpoled.

Synopsis: Jaheira's default dialogue. Topics range from her past life to her current goals as they develop. Unless otherwise stated, her tone is confident and to the point. She's a seasoned adventurer with a sardonic sense of humour - and a little less cynical than she might present herself to be.
